WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.500 --> 00:00:04.200
This is the fine-structure constant — how strongly light and matter interact.

2
00:00:04.200 --> 00:00:08.600
Physics measures it. TFPT computes it — the one answer a short equation allows,

3
00:00:08.600 --> 00:00:11.600
fixed by just two numbers, and nothing else.

4
00:00:11.600 --> 00:00:14.900
Bold claim. So I'll also show you exactly where it could break.

5
00:00:15.400 --> 00:00:19.600
Think of TFPT as a compiler — not a table of lucky numbers, but a machine.

6
00:00:19.600 --> 00:00:24.600
Two inputs go in: a boundary constant, c₃ = 1/(8π) — the rule for an edge of space,

7
00:00:24.600 --> 00:00:29.000
and a carrier, g_car = 5 — how the building blocks plug together.

8
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:34.500
From only those two, one shape is forced to assemble: the exceptional group E₈.

9
00:00:34.500 --> 00:00:40.000
But here's the twist — E₈ is not a force of nature.

10
00:00:40.000 --> 00:00:46.000
It's a scaffold: a consistency check you build, verify against, then step away from.

11
00:00:46.000 --> 00:00:55.000
The Standard Model isn't "everything is E₈" — it's what you read off after projecting back down.

12
00:00:55.400 --> 00:00:59.800
So what does the machine print out?

13
00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:05.500
First, a discrete skeleton — exact and machine-checked, with no wiggle room:

14
00:01:05.500 --> 00:01:11.000
three generations of matter, the right charges, the 240 roots of E₈,

15
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.500
and the same small numbers everywhere — two, three, five.

16
00:01:15.500 --> 00:01:21.500
Then the headline: the fine-structure constant is the single positive root of one cubic.

17
00:01:21.500 --> 00:01:26.800
Not chosen — forced. α⁻¹ = 137.0359992,

18
00:01:26.800 --> 00:01:31.000
less than two sigma from the measured value.

19
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.900
Not a fit. A forced answer.

20
00:01:35.400 --> 00:01:39.500
The same discipline runs through the particle masses.

21
00:01:39.500 --> 00:01:45.000
They don't come from dozens of free dials —

22
00:01:45.000 --> 00:01:51.000
but from one pattern: a single seed, a fixed matrix, and whole-number steps.

23
00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:55.800
Mixing angles and the leading CP phase drop out of the same geometry.

24
00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:59.900
The one honest unit they still need, we flag — we don't hide it.

25
00:02:00.400 --> 00:02:04.500
And that first input hides a gift.

26
00:02:04.500 --> 00:02:10.000
c₃ = 1/(8π) is the exact 8π sitting inside Einstein's equation for gravity.

27
00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:15.500
Run the same atoms through the heat of a horizon, and the full law of gravity falls out —

28
00:02:15.500 --> 00:02:20.000
both constants fixed, even the cosmological constant, set by α.

29
00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:25.900
The same 1/(8π) shows up three independent ways. Hard to call that an accident.

30
00:02:26.400 --> 00:02:31.000
Small whole numbers raise a fair worry: is this just numerology?

31
00:02:31.000 --> 00:02:34.500
So we tried to break it ourselves.

32
00:02:34.500 --> 00:02:40.500
We froze thirteen predictions, then ran two hundred thousand random look-alike theories.

33
00:02:40.500 --> 00:02:45.000
TFPT hits all thirteen. The random ones top out at five.

34
00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:51.000
For α: of ninety-four thousand variants, exactly one lands in the measured window.

35
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:57.000
Seven completely different number systems each rebuild the same skeleton.

36
00:02:57.000 --> 00:03:02.500
And we publish what E₈ does not use — five of its eight pieces carry no prediction.

37
00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:09.000
Odds a look-alike matches the whole scorecard: below 10⁻³⁰. Checked twice — in Wolfram and in Lean.

38
00:03:09.400 --> 00:03:13.500
Now the honest part — how would you kill it?

39
00:03:13.500 --> 00:03:18.500
Every prediction was sealed in a registry before any comparison.

40
00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:24.000
sin²θ₁₂ ≈ 0.3067.  sin²θ₁₃ ≈ 0.0231.  A tiny gravitational-wave ratio.  Normal neutrino ordering.

41
00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:28.500
Today, all of them sit within about one sigma.

42
00:03:28.500 --> 00:03:34.500
The near-term tests are real: neutrino mass from DESI and CMB-S4,

43
00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:38.900
and proton decay at Hyper-Kamiokande. One clean miss, and it's wrong.

44
00:03:39.400 --> 00:03:43.500
So what is actually still open?

45
00:03:43.500 --> 00:03:48.500
Not a vague pile — three named, labelled handoffs.

46
00:03:48.500 --> 00:03:54.000
One published-theorem step from closing the central seam,

47
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:59.000
the clearly-marked bridges to external physics,

48
00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:05.000
and one honest unit — because a theorem says pure numbers can never hand you a kilogram.

49
00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:10.000
Zero hidden mechanisms. Two inputs, one compiler — fully audited.

